{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536418"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:06:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:06:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15779"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15779"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.41,0.01,0.15,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8470"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102710"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8470"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85193"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"3833"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40842"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102710"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of a bleeding lesion on his right lower leg. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He lives independently and previously worked as a farmer for 40 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 1.5 cm erythematous, indurated, and ulcerated lesion on the lateral aspect of his right lower leg (Image). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biopsy of the skin lesion","Excision with 4 mm surgical margins","Computed tomography of chest, abdomen, and pelvis","Clinical examination of regional lymph nodes","Neurovascular assessment of the right leg"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a suspicious lesion that has features consistent with cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (SCC), including ulceration, induration, and bleeding. Given the location and presentation, a systematic approach to assessment is crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical examination of regional lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. For lesions on the lower leg, this involves examining the popliteal and inguinal lymph node basins. Lymphatic spread is the most common route of metastasis for cutaneous SCC, and clinical examination can identify early spread that would alter management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiopsy of the skin lesion\u003C/strong\u003E would typically follow the lymph node assessment. While histological confirmation is necessary, the regional lymph node status is more critical for determining the extent of disease and planning appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcision with 4 mm surgical margins\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature without first establishing the extent of disease and confirming the diagnosis histologically. The appropriate margin width depends on various factors including tumour size, location, and risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography of chest, abdomen, and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely indicated for cutaneous SCC. Imaging would only be warranted if there were high-risk features (such as size \u0026gt;2cm, poor differentiation, depth \u0026gt;6mm) or if lymphadenopathy was detected on clinical examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurovascular assessment of the right leg\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide relevant information for staging or management of the suspected skin malignancy. While important for surgical planning, it is not the most appropriate next step in assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for cutaneous SCC include chronic sun exposure (relevant given the patient\u0027s farming history), age, and immunosuppression. The lower leg is considered a high-risk site due to poorer healing and higher recurrence rates. After completing the assessment, management typically involves wide local excision with appropriate margins based on risk stratification.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clinical examination of regional lymph nodes is essential in the assessment of cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma.","High-risk features of cutaneous SCC include location on lower limbs, size \u003E2cm, poor differentiation, and depth \u003E6mm.","Imaging is only indicated for high-risk SCCs or when lymphadenopathy is detected on clinical examination."],"references":["Stratigos AJ, et al. European interdisciplinary guideline on invasive squamous cell carcinoma of the skin: Part 1. epidemiology, diagnostics and prevention. Eur J Cancer. 2020;128:60-82."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85193"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15779"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21184"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21184"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3saskQcUmMEpq